Apologies, but the solution to logic sheet 6 question 4(e) contains 
an error.  It is not true that there is only one assignment showing 
the sentence to be false.  You can also take x=c, y=a.  This makes 
the RHS true (since you can take z=b), but the LHS false (since P(c) 
is false).

This has now been corrected in the solutions on the web at 
http://www.doc.ic.ac.uk/~imh/teaching/140_logic/ex6.pdf


Re. sheet 7, Q2-4, I forgot to say that "-" (minus) is allowed as 
well as +, x (and I used "-" in Q2).  - is interpreted in the natural 
way, but the value of x-y when y>x is arbitrary (unpredictable).

Ian H

